A hinge that comes apart easily by lifting up. After browsing Thingiverse for quite a while to find a hinge that would easily detach from my bot and not finding anything I created a couple. I just added a few pics of the hinge in action! Pay no attention to the crack in the plexiglass... It works! Now I just need to find or design a latch to keep it closed. Hinge2.stl seems better suited if your acrylic is on top of the wood rather than flush with it. Just designed and printed a knob/latch for the doors:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:19695

I was looking for a printable hinge to possibly attach acrylic panels that I could open on the sides and back of my makerbot.
Print and if necessary smooth the peg and install.
If your surface is flush the hinge can be converted for flush mount or non-flush by rotating the one half.
If you want to install it on the other side of your bot you'll probably have to mirror the print in ReplicatorG so the pin is up.

description.text:
This is a simple and easy to print miniature lighthouse. I created this in Solidworks for myself, and I figured I might as well share it with the community.

I plan on painting it and fitting a pulsing high power LED in it, and then mounting it atop a rocky island sculpted from high-density foam.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Based off a number of other similar designs, this fan setup uses 1 x 40mm x 10mm axial fan for the hot end cooling. On the sides are two standard 4020S blower fans.

The print, with the two fans weighs 78g.

I tried to keep the whole design as small as possible so the head can reach the outside of the print bed without the fans hitting anything.

Update: Feb 6, 2017 - If your effector doesn't use Traxxas joints but uses the larger bearing ends, use the fan STL labeled "Extra Clearance". It drops the fans low enough under the effector to clear the large bearings, but maintains the original height of the design.

Update: May 14, 2017 - Uploaded an adjustable vent version for those that want to direct the airflow. The STL files have the "ADJ" in them. I am using it on an E3D V5 but I don't think it enough to accommodate an E3D V6.

Printer:

Kossel

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm

Infill:

50%

Notes:

While the fans can be connected to a RAMPs board for control, I prefer manual control so I connect them to a simple PWM control found just about anywhere on the net. The majority of the time when cooling is needed on a print, I have the PWM control pot set about 60%, when doing single wall vase mode, 80% or more if printing something like a rocket nose.

The fans are mounted in such a way that the Traxxas rod ends will not touch the fans. The effector mount will also clear the fans.

The Kossel/Delta I am using this on has an effector plate with 40mm spacing mounts so it's not going to fit on a Mini Kossel. The hot end I am using is an E3D-V5 and the nozzle extends 6mm below.

M3 screws are used to attach the fans ( 3 per blower fan, 4 for the axial head cooling fan).

For the adjustable vent version, be warned the vents are a SNUG fit! I print the vents with 50% infill, slow (30mm/s) and 0.2 layer height. The hole in the fan housing is 10mm and the vents are 10mm in diameter. If you want some wiggle room, scale the vent pieces ever so slightly. I prefer them tight so they don't ever move once adjusted.

Note also that the fan setup will only work with Traxxas rod ends.

description.text:
A combination lock for a swinging door. Security is provided by three wheels with 6 numbers each. Size is approximately 100m x 50mm x 30mm. Wheels have internal springs to self align to the numbers.

Select the combination by choosing the corresponding "CL_wheel#.STL" model. A blank wheel is also included.

For the 4 digit version you just need 2 different parts: CL_cylinder_4digits and CL_frame_m1_4digits.

Made as part of a present for a kid: A private pirate chest.

Notes:

Please select proper print orientation on your own. Manual support is supplied for some files.

Remove the support. Push each of the internal springs within the wheels to the outside to free them.

Put the first wheel onto the cylinder, press the 2nd pin into the hole, put the 2nd wheel onto the cylinder, put the 3rd pin into the hole, put the 3rd wheel onto the cylinder, put the assembly into the frame and finally push the last frame part into its position. You should use super glue to fixate the separated frame. After screwing in the screws you can put the rivets onto the screws to hide them.

description.text:
Would you like to test your new filament's temperature range? This temperature tower is ideal for you.

It is fully customizable - width, depth, number of elements, text embossing, etc.

Just open temptower.scad in OpenSCAD, modify properties as you want. Render it (it takes some time), save it as .STL.

Open .STL in your favorite slicer, use always the same layer height (e.g. 0.2mm), slice it and save G-CODE somewhere.

And run Python script tempinjector.py with the corresponding parameters, e.g.:
python tempinjector.py tt.gcode tt.modified.gcode 250 -5 5.0

This simple script replace and add new extruder temperatures to the g-code at appropriate levels.

Just print modified g-code file.

Tested with Slic3r and Repetier.

When I started 3D printing I figured out like everyone else that spools was a problem, since they come in differents size and had something in mind to design to try to enhance the filament holder, but I had tons of things to print before.
When I checked Thingiverse about spool filaments I found PHIL that was a similar design of what I had in mind (idea came with the ANET A8 spool holder that could almost handle this) and I finally took time for it and downloaded/printed to find out that it wasnt working (yeah Ill read comments before now) :/ so, back to work.

There is my vision of an working universal spool holder fully printed.
I uploaded videos to show it can work with new and almost empty spool, with 2 positions, upward and downward.

Additionally it should be PHIL compatible, which mean that you can print Pins and Spools only to put them on.

Printing :
Print pins vertically and spool horizontaly to limit friction when assembled.

Assembly:
Once printed, clean all the pieces.
For optimal use, inside spool can be sanded but not necessary if your printing is good.
Fit the pins in spools and snap them fully in stand.

Attach them to...something, desk, wood, whatever with screws and ajust them according your filament spool using the slider.
A guide is not necessary but can be used, Ill upload one soon as an update.

title: C170 MP Select Mini Camera Mount (Universal Glass Bed)

description.text:
I fixed an Issue with the original and made it work with a glass bed. This is my first remix and I don't know how to edit .STL files so I just remade it in Sketchup.

The main reason I made this was because the original would not work with the glass bed since the clips wouldn't expand enough for the mount and the glass bed. As well as it was too wide to add its own clips. So while I was making it less wide I decided I'd fix the issue with the C170 Camera being off center since the lens is offset. So I shortened it and made a cut out for the second clip. Works well if you insert the clip before hand like the picture.

Now if you look at the pic from the camera mounted on the bed it is centered. Uses the 3/4" binder clips from Walmart or elsewhere.

I used this video to install the glass bed: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CJDYKqbRuQY&t=1820s
I used an 1/8" thick 5" x 5" Borosilicate Glass Sheet from here: https://www.mcmaster.com/#standard-borosilicate-glass/=15dtmqj
Instead of the Z-axis spacer in the vid above I used this one customized for 1/8" glass: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1942794

Enjoy and thanks to the original designer: http://www.thingiverse.com/PrintersParadise/about

description.text:
This is a y-axis stabilization kit for the Solidoodle 3. One of the things you'll notice with the SD3 is that nozzle drag occasionally causes significant vibrations in the y-axis, especially at the end of the build platform. This is a problem for many, MANY printers.  
This kit solves the problem. It requires three non-printed parts: a carbon fiber (or aluminum) rod and two 11mm bearings. It can be easily modified for whatever you have lying around, though.  
You're also welcome to break apart the kit and make whatever you want from the parts. It should be easy to modify for any other printer that has a build platform and something to ride the bearings against.

There are two STL files. You'll need to print "Clamps.stl" once. It has the left and right clips for the build platform. You'll need to print "BearingHolder" twice, one for each end. It has the holder for the bearing and an axle pin. Parts List: • 2 - prints of "Bearing Holders"
• 1 - print of "Clamps"
• 1 - 4mm Carbon Fiber Rod. You can find this at just about any hobby shop.
• 2 - 11mm/5mm/4mm bearing, also found at any RC or hobby shop. Instructions:
  • Test the fit of the clamps on your build platform and check to make sure you know which is left and which is right.
  • Slide the left and right clamps onto the 4mm carbon fiber rod.
  • Check the fit of the rod and cut to fit about 10mm from the inside of each frame in the Solidoodle.
  • Build two bearing holders. Slide a bearing into a holder and press the pin axle through one side of the holder, through the bearing, and out through the other side. Set with glue.
  • Fit the bearing holders to the end of your carbon fiber rod. Check fit inside the printer, sand the rod as needed until the bearing ride against sides of the printer without bending the rod. A little bit of slack is okay (1-2mm).
  • Hot glue the bearing holders onto the rod. Lay flat on a table to align them.
  • Slide the rig into the printer and onto the platform.
  • Print!

description.text:
This is my entry for the Thingiverse Remix Challenge. I've been on a dwarf kick lately, so the first thing in the collection that caught my eye was bendansie's fantastic Bearded Yell bust. Using Meshmixer to cut a chunk off the pedestal, I used MakerBot Desktop to arrange the head/beard into the body parts I used for my recent space dwarf model, Ulfer Ironhead. I'd always wanted to use atartanian's Beefy Arms, so I figured this was a good a time as any. As I was posing them, I realized that this guy would look best rocking a sweet flying v, so I cobbled together a miniature guitar using bits from Roy-Tore Hofstad's awesome AMGP using TinkerCAD (along with his studded bracer). I used a combination of Sculptris and TinkerCAD to make his rocky base, ran him through netfabb, and the rest is (rock) history.

I've included a "statue" version and a 28mm scale version (for all you fellow tabletoppers). You'll want to print this guy with support material (took us round 11 hours for the statue version).

We've set up a Patreon page for anyone who's interested in helping to fund us so we can keep making free and open sourced games like Pocket-Tactics, Wayfarer Tactics. and others, not to mention the growing catalog of gaming miniatures that you can use for whatever you want! (Psst... we take requests and commissions...)

Enjoy!

description.text:
This is a Seifert surface for the trefoil knot described the the equation in spherical coordinates:

4 r cos(p) = 4 cos(p) + sin(3t) sin(p),

with the restriction:

| sin(3t/2) tan(p) | < 1/2

Here, r (rho) is the distance from the origin, p (phi) is the angle from the positive z-axis (latitude) and t (theta) is the angle in the xy-plane from the positive x-axis measured counterclockwise.

I had never seen a closed-form equation for a Seifert surface before, so I decided it would be fun to figure one out.

I used Mathematica to design this thing. While I had an equation for the surface, Mathematica's plotting algorithm works best with a parametrization. The surface is not isomorphic to any part of the plane, so a single parametrization would not be possible. I ended up parametrizing the surface in five parts.

The top and bottom patches were parametrized by solving for *r* as a function of *p* and *t*. The three twists were parametrized by solving for *t* as a function of *r* and *p*. The five patches smoothly connected. The domain for *t* and *p*.
Camera Reflex in two parts, to make it easier to print.

title: Handle and top cap for Silca track bicycle tire pump

description.text:
Broke the handle on my vintage Silca track pump, measured and determined the thread on the pump shaft is an M10x1.5, so figured I could make my own handle. Got a custom M10x1.5 nut from the Nut Job thing, imported it into SketchUp and ditched the outside parts and just used the thread. Designed the handle using some quick measurements and guess work, and since I always use this pump one-handed (holding the chuck on the valve with the other) I designed it for one-hand use, and have to say I think I nailed the shape. Feels great to pump, way better than the much smaller original handle.

While I was fitting things, I noticed that although the top cap wasn't broken, I could print up a replacement and include clips to mount the pump hose, one thing that was lacking from the original.

Amusingly enough, I remember some cars (Acura Integra, so probably most Hondas) that I've worked on that had an M10x1.50 thread on the shift lever, so this pump handle could actually be used as a shift knob on one of those cars. Almost wish I still had one.

Monoprice Maker Ultimate

No

Yes

33% triangles

Notes:

Originally tried printing the handle vertically (on the side edge) so I could avoid any supports, but after two failed prints with bed adhesion problems, I decided to lay it flat (threads down) and put a small amount of support under it. That worked. The top cap prints fine with no supports as-is, with the top down on the print bed.

One thing to watch out for - on my first print of the top cap, threading in the screw that holds it in place caused it to crack due to layer adhesion problems. I was going to resize the hole on the side to 3.8mm to address this, but SketchUp was annoying me, so on the reprint I just drilled out the hole to 5/32" to avoid the cracking issues.

description.text:
This is the wide-body version of my modified SEEJ torsion catapult. I think it's much better!

I'll leave the skinny one available here if you would rather have that one. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1923579

The width matches the length of an average rubber band much more closely, so you don't waste twists taking up slack before you can build tension.

I also made a second arm to choose from that fits marbles, and included some balls that fit really well. There's a caddy that will still mount to the side of the engine that has a slight angle, so balls will roll to the back.

The atlas was further modified to launch at a 60 degree angle, giving it some more time to deliver some kinetic energy before it hits and releases. To compensate, I extended my height bar even further, so you just have to tilt the engine to get the lower angles.

I widened the 'foramen' even more so that more bands could be threaded.
About 3 turns of each key got me a 10 foot shot! It's certainly capable of much more!

The compass origin was moved again so that it sits right below the release point. This should give further accuracy.

This project was used as a visual aid along with a few others for my sixth grade class, who built their own scale projectile motion machines with many of the same features.
